#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""check-green-doc-tense — DF-GREEN-DOC-TENSE-SWEEP enforcement gate.

Scans tracked test files (tests/*.rs and src/**/*.rs cfg(test) modules) for
comment lines that assert current-state RED/stub behaviour on code that is
now GREEN. These are "stale RED-phase headers" — section or file-level
comments written during the TDD Red Gate phase that were never removed when
the implementation was shipped.

PROBLEM PATTERN
---------------
During strict TDD, test files are written before implementation with module-
level or section-level comments like:

    //! All tests MUST FAIL (todo!() panic) before implementation — Red Gate
    // PART A: stub-only bodies — panic!("STORY-019 stub — Red Gate").
    // All test bodies panic — Red Gate (Part A stubs).

These comments become stale after the GREEN phase: the implementation ships,
the todo!() stubs are replaced with real assertions, but the headers are left
behind. The prose now actively misleads readers into thinking the tests are
expected to fail (Red) when they are actually passing (Green).

This gate catches those stale headers so they are scrubbed before merge.

TOKEN LIST (lines to flag — current-state assertions)
------------------------------------------------------
The following patterns are matched against COMMENT LINES ONLY
(lines whose non-whitespace content starts with // or //!):

  1. All tests MUST FAIL
  2. ALL tests must fail
  3. All tests in this file are designed to FAIL
  4. RED GATE:.*tests must fail         (case-insensitive on "must fail" tail)
  5. RED GATE: ALL tests must fail
  6. All stubs panic to satisfy the Red Gate
  7. All test bodies panic.*Red Gate
  8. PART A: stub-only bodies.*panic
  9. stub-only bodies.*panic.*Red Gate
 10. Every test body panics.*must FAIL before
 11. All stubs MUST fail before
 12. RED[  ]*[-—]+[  ]*stubs only      — module-level "RED — stubs only" or "RED -- stubs only"
 13. All tests are RED until            — current-state "tests are RED" assertion
 14. RED (STORY-NNN stub)               — per-test docstring stub-phase marker
 15. todo!() until STORY-NNN implements  — "todo!() until STORY-NNN implements"
 16. will panic at .* until the implementation lands  — "will panic … until implementation"
 17. tests? will panic .* until .* implement  — "test(s) will panic … until … implement"
 18. Each test will panic at .* until        — "Each test will panic at … until"
 19. before reaching .*todo!()          — GREEN-BY-DESIGN docstring referencing a now-gone todo!()
                                          block (e.g. "gate fires before reaching the todo!() Stop-detection block")
 20. no todo!() is reached             — GREEN-BY-DESIGN docstring asserting todo!() is bypassed
                                          (e.g. "no todo!() is reached", "No todo!() is reached because")
 21. before any todo!() block          — GREEN-BY-DESIGN docstring stating execution returns before
                                          any todo!() block (e.g. "fires before any todo!() block")
 22. todo!() (Stop|Reset|.*-detection) block — docstring naming a specific detection block as todo!()
                                          (e.g. "todo!() Stop-detection block", "todo!() Reset block")

All patterns are anchored to comment lines (leading // or //!) to avoid
false-positives inside doc-test code blocks or inside string literals.

ALLOWLIST (lines NOT flagged — legitimate past-tense or contextual prose)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
The allowlist is implemented by the token specificity above: every pattern
requires an unambiguous current-state assertion ("MUST FAIL", "are designed
to FAIL", "stub-only bodies", "stubs only", "are RED until", etc.) that
cannot appear in past-tense provenance narration.

Pattern-specific allowlist notes (patterns 12-22):
  12. "RED — stubs only": The dash+phrase combination is specific to stub-phase
      headers. Past-tense equivalents use "originated as stubs" or "were stubs".
      Allowlisted: "originated as Red-Gate stubs", "(was RED)", patterns without
      the dash+stubs-only suffix.
  13. "All tests are RED until": The present-tense "are RED" is unambiguous.
      Allowlisted: "were RED until", "tests passed their RED phase".
  14. "RED (STORY-NNN stub)": The parenthesised (STORY-NNN stub) suffix is used
      exclusively in stub-phase doc-comment headers. Not used in past-tense prose.
      Allowlisted: "originated as STORY-NNN stub", "STORY-NNN stub (GREEN)".
  15. "todo!() until STORY-NNN implements": Unambiguous current-state assertion.
      Allowlisted: "todo!() was replaced", "todo!() stub is now GREEN".
  16. "will panic at … until the implementation lands": Unambiguous future-state
      assertion meaning the code currently panics. Allowlisted: "would panic",
      "used to panic", "panicked before implementation".
  17. "test(s) will panic … until … implement": Same rationale as 16.
      Allowlisted: "tests panicked", "tests would panic".
  19. "before reaching .*todo!()": Present-tense framing implies todo!() still
      exists in the code as an active stub. The test describing itself as "firing
      before reaching todo!()" only makes sense if todo!() is still live.
      Allowlisted: "the todo!() was replaced", "originated as todo!() stubs" —
      past-tense forms that document historical context without asserting current state.
  20. "no todo!() is reached": Same rationale — describes todo!() as a currently-live
      code path that the test short-circuits. After implementation is green, there is no
      todo!() to reach.
      Allowlisted: "the todo!() was replaced in STORY-NNN" — past-tense provenance.
  21. "before any todo!() block": Present-tense form asserting the function still
      contains active todo!() blocks the test bypasses. Post-implementation, no
      todo!() blocks remain; this framing is always stale on green code.
      Allowlisted: "before any todo!() block was replaced" — grammatically past-tense.
  22. "todo!() (Stop|Reset|.*-detection) block": Names a specific feature block by
      its todo!() stub label (e.g. "todo!() Stop-detection block"). Once implemented,
      the block is no longer a todo!() — it is the detection logic itself. Referring
      to it as a "todo!() block" in a docstring is stale once the code is green.
      Allowlisted: "the todo!() Stop-detection block was replaced", "originated as
      todo!() stubs" — past-tense or provenance framing. NOT flagged: prose using
      past tense like "the todo!() was replaced" or "originated as todo!() stubs".

The following commonly-seen "Red Gate" phrases are intentionally NOT in the
token list because they describe historical provenance, not current state:

  - "passed their Red Gate phase"          — past tense, narrative
  - "originally written as a Red Gate"     — past tense, narrative
  - "Red Gate for AC-NNN"                  — historical reference
  - "Red Gate assertion" (in doc comments) — describes nature of a test
  - "Red Gate commit"                      — git history reference
  - "RED-phase:" (in doc-comment headers)  — provenance section, past tense
  - "making this a reliable Red Gate"      — describes statistical property
  - "deterministic Red Gate in all senses" — describes test reliability
  - "must fail" as an inline test assertion — e.g. "strict must fail with
    SliceError::Len" inside test body prose; these appear mid-sentence in
    doc comments and are test-contract narration, not stub-phase headers.
  - "implementer adds / must add" — too broad; "implementer" appears in
    many legitimate past-tense and future-guidance comments.

SELF-TEST
---------
Run: python3 bin/test_check_green_doc_tense.py
"""

import re
import subprocess
import sys
from pathlib import Path


# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Token patterns — each is a regex matched against a comment line.
# A "comment line" is one where the stripped content starts with // or //!
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

_VIOLATION_PATTERNS: list[tuple[str, re.Pattern[str]]] = [
    (
        "All tests MUST FAIL (module-level RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"All tests MUST FAIL", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        "ALL tests must fail (module-level RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"ALL tests must fail"),
    ),
    (
        "All tests in this file are designed to FAIL (RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"All tests in this file are designed to FAIL", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        "RED GATE: … tests must fail (section RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"RED GATE:.*tests must fail", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        "All stubs panic to satisfy the Red Gate (section RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"All stubs panic to satisfy the Red Gate", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        "All test bodies panic — Red Gate (section RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"All test bodies panic.*Red Gate", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        "PART A: stub-only bodies — panic (section RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"PART A: stub-only bodies.*panic", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        "stub-only bodies — panic — Red Gate (section RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"stub-only bodies.*panic.*Red Gate", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        "Every test body panics; all must FAIL before (section RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"Every test body panics.*must FAIL before", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        "All stubs MUST fail before (section RED-stub header)",
        re.compile(r"All stubs MUST fail before", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    # -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    # Patterns 12-17: added to catch feature-enip stale RED phrasings that
    # slipped through the original gate (F-135-002 / adversarial Pass 1).
    # -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    (
        # Pattern 12: "RED — stubs only" / "RED -- stubs only" (em-dash or double-hyphen).
        # These are module-level headers written during stub phase and never scrubbed.
        # Allowlist: "originated as Red-Gate stubs", "(was RED)" — neither contains
        # the dash+stubs-only suffix.
        "RED — stubs only (module-level stub-phase header; em-dash or double-hyphen variant)",
        re.compile(r"RED\s*[-—]{1,2}\s*stubs only", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        # Pattern 13: "All tests are RED until" — present-tense current-state assertion.
        # Allowlist: "were RED until", "tests passed their RED phase" — different tense.
        "All tests are RED until (current-state RED assertion in module header)",
        re.compile(r"All tests are RED until", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        # Pattern 14: "RED (STORY-NNN stub)" — per-test docstring stub-phase marker.
        # The parenthesised (STORY-NNN stub) is used exclusively during stub phase.
        # Allowlist: "originated as STORY-NNN stub", "STORY-NNN stub (GREEN)" — different structure.
        "RED (STORY-NNN stub) (per-test stub-phase docstring marker)",
        re.compile(r"RED\s*\(STORY-\d+\s+stub\)", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        # Pattern 15: "todo!() until STORY-NNN implements" — asserts todo!() is still live.
        # The todo!() may be backtick-wrapped (`` `todo!()` ``), so we allow non-word chars
        # between the closing paren and "until": `todo!\(\)\W+until`.
        # Allowlist: "todo!() was replaced", "todo!() stub is now GREEN".
        "todo!() until STORY-NNN implements (current-state todo!() stub assertion)",
        re.compile(r"todo!\(\)\W+until\s+STORY-\d+\s+implement", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        # Pattern 16: "will panic at … until the implementation lands" — states the code
        # currently panics (present/future tense pointing at a live stub).
        # Allowlist: "would panic", "used to panic", "panicked before implementation".
        "will panic … until the implementation lands (current-state panic assertion)",
        re.compile(r"will panic\b.*\buntil the implementation lands", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        # Pattern 17: "test(s) will panic … until … implement" — variant of pattern 16.
        # Allowlist: "tests panicked", "tests would panic".
        "test(s) will panic … until … implement (current-state panic assertion)",
        re.compile(r"tests?\s+will panic\b.*\buntil\b.*\bimplement", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        # Pattern 18: "Each test will panic at … until" — catches the recon module header
        # pattern where the "implementation lands" tail wraps to the next line. The phrase
        # "Each test will panic at … until" is unambiguously a current-state stub assertion.
        # Allowlist: "Each test would have panicked", "Each test panicked before".
        "Each test will panic at … until (current-state per-test panic assertion in header)",
        re.compile(r"Each test will panic at\b.*\buntil\b", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    # -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    # Patterns 19-22: added to catch stale GREEN-BY-DESIGN todo!() references
    # in STORY-135 command_detections and sibling mods (F-135-P3-001).
    # These patterns fire on comment lines that assert the code still contains
    # active todo!() blocks — stale after the implementation ships GREEN.
    # -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    (
        # Pattern 19: "before reaching .*todo!()" — present-tense claim that a live
        # todo!() block exists downstream of a short-circuiting gate.
        # Examples: "gate fires in the CPF loop before reaching the todo!() Stop-detection block"
        #           "gate fires before reaching todo!() Reset block"
        # Allowlist: "the todo!() was replaced", "originated as todo!() stubs" — past-tense.
        "before reaching … todo!() (stale GREEN-BY-DESIGN docstring referencing a now-gone stub)",
        re.compile(r"before reaching\b.*\btodo!\(\)", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        # Pattern 20: "no todo!() is reached" — present-tense assertion that todo!()
        # is bypassed, implying it still exists in the code.
        # Examples: "no todo!() is reached", "No todo!() is reached because the function returns"
        # Allowlist: "the todo!() was replaced in STORY-NNN" — past-tense provenance.
        "no todo!() is reached (stale GREEN-BY-DESIGN docstring asserting todo!() is bypassed)",
        re.compile(r"no\s+todo!\(\)\s+is\s+reached", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        # Pattern 21: "before any todo!() block" — present-tense assertion that todo!()
        # blocks still exist in the function body.
        # Examples: "the is_non_enip early-return fires before any todo!() block"
        # Allowlist: past-tense forms — "before any todo!() block was replaced".
        "before any todo!() block (stale GREEN-BY-DESIGN docstring asserting live todo!() blocks)",
        re.compile(r"before any\s+todo!\(\)\s+block", re.IGNORECASE),
    ),
    (
        # Pattern 22: "todo!() <detection-name> block" — names a specific detection
        # feature block using its stub-phase todo!() label (e.g. "todo!() Stop-detection block",
        # "todo!() Reset block"). Once GREEN, the block is the detection logic, not a stub.
        # Examples: "reaching the todo!() Stop-detection block"
        #           "before reaching todo!() Reset block"
        # Allowlist: past-tense — "the todo!() Stop-detection block was replaced",
        #            "originated as todo!() stubs".
        # Note: Pattern 19 already catches the "before reaching" form; Pattern 22 catches
        # any remaining standalone "todo!() <detection> block" references.
        # Negative lookahead on " was" distinguishes "block was replaced" (past, allowlisted)
        # from "block." or "block runs" (present-state, flagged).
        "todo!() <detection> block (stale stub-phase label on a now-implemented block)",
        re.compile(
            r"todo!\(\)\s+(?:Stop|Reset|Stop-detection|Reset-detection|"
            r"\w+-detection)\s+block(?!\s+was\b)",
            re.IGNORECASE,
        ),
    ),
]


def _is_comment_line(stripped: str) -> bool:
    """Return True if the stripped line starts with a Rust comment marker."""
    return stripped.startswith("//")


def _collect_rust_files(repo_root: Path) -> list[Path]:
    """
    Collect test-scope Rust files:
      - tests/*.rs    (integration test files)
      - src/**/*.rs   (may contain #[cfg(test)] modules)

    Only tracked files are considered (git ls-files). Untracked files are
    excluded so newly-added test files do not cause false failures before
    their first commit.
    """
    result = subprocess.run(
        ["git", "ls-files", "--", "tests/*.rs", "src/**/*.rs"],
        cwd=repo_root,
        capture_output=True,
        text=True,
        check=True,
    )
    paths = []
    resolved_root = repo_root.resolve()
    for line in result.stdout.splitlines():
        line = line.strip()
        if line.endswith(".rs"):
            p = (repo_root / line).resolve()
            # SEC-001: reject any path that escapes the repo root (e.g. absolute
            # paths or ../traversal components that git ls-files should never emit,
            # but we defend in depth).
            if not str(p).startswith(str(resolved_root)):
                continue
            if p.exists():
                paths.append(p)
    return paths


def scan_file(path: Path) -> list[tuple[int, str, str]]:
    """
    Scan one file. Returns a list of (lineno, line_content, violation_label)
    for each offending line.
    """
    violations: list[tuple[int, str, str]] = []
    try:
        text = path.read_text(encoding="utf-8")
    except OSError as exc:
        # Unreadable file: report as a scan error, not a gate failure.
        print(f"WARNING: cannot read {path}: {exc}", file=sys.stderr)
        return violations

    for lineno, raw_line in enumerate(text.splitlines(), start=1):
        stripped = raw_line.strip()
        if not _is_comment_line(stripped):
            continue
        for label, pattern in _VIOLATION_PATTERNS:
            if pattern.search(stripped):
                violations.append((lineno, raw_line.rstrip(), label))
                break  # one label per line is enough

    return violations


def main() -> int:
    # Resolve repo root: walk up from this script's location until we find
    # a directory containing a .git entry (file or directory).
    script_path = Path(__file__).resolve()
    candidate = script_path.parent
    repo_root: Path | None = None
    for _ in range(6):  # at most 6 levels up
        if (candidate / ".git").exists() or (candidate / "Cargo.toml").exists():
            repo_root = candidate
            break
        candidate = candidate.parent
    if repo_root is None:
        print("ERROR: could not locate repo root (no .git or Cargo.toml found)", file=sys.stderr)
        return 2

    rust_files = _collect_rust_files(repo_root)
    if not rust_files:
        print("WARNING: no tracked Rust files found; scan target may be wrong.", file=sys.stderr)

    total_violations = 0
    for path in sorted(rust_files):
        rel = path.relative_to(repo_root)
        file_violations = scan_file(path)
        for lineno, content, label in file_violations:
            print(f"FAIL [{rel}:{lineno}]: {label}")
            print(f"     {content}")
            total_violations += 1

    if total_violations > 0:
        print()
        print(
            f"Found {total_violations} stale RED-phase comment(s) in test files "
            f"(DF-GREEN-DOC-TENSE-SWEEP)."
        )
        print(
            "These comment lines assert that tests currently fail (Red Gate / stub-phase),"
        )
        print(
            "but the test bodies beneath them contain real assertions (the code is GREEN)."
        )
        print(
            "Scrub or replace each comment to reflect current GREEN status before merging."
        )
        return 1

    print(f"PASS: no stale RED-phase comment headers found ({len(rust_files)} files scanned).")
    return 0


if __name__ == "__main__":
    sys.exit(main())
